GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 269
Short Title: Workforce Freedom and Protection Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Cohn, Crawford, K. Brown, and Logan (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Commerce and Economic Development, if favorable, Judiciary 2, if favorable,
Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
March 5, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT REMOVING BARRIERS TO JOB MOBILITY, EMPOWERING WORKERS TO
3 NEGOTIATE BETTER WAGES, AND FOSTERING A FAIRER LABOR MARKET BY
4 BANNING EXPLOITATIVE EMPLOYMENT PRACTICES AND AUTHORIZING THE
5 LEGISLATIVE RESEARCH COMMISSION TO STUDY STREAMLINING
6 OCCUPATIONAL LICENSING IN NORTH CAROLINA.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8 SECTION 1.1. Title. – This act shall be known and may be cited as the "Workforce
9 Freedom and Protection Act."
10 SECTION 2.1. Repeal Restrictions on Labor Organizing and Collective Bargaining.
11 – Articles 10 and 12 of Chapter 95 of the General Statutes are repealed.
12 SECTION 3.1.(a) Non-Competes Prohibited. – Chapter 95 of the General Statutes
13 is amended by adding a new Article to read:
14 "Article 24.
15 "Workplace Freedom.
16 "§ 95-275. Contracts restraining lawful work prohibited.
17 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this Article:
18 (1) Employee. – An employee providing labor or services to another for pay of
19 less than seventy–five thousand dollars ($75,000) per year.
20 (2) Non-compete agreement. – An agreement between an employer and an
21 employee that restricts the employee, after termination of the employment,
22 from doing one or more of the following:
23 a. Working for another employer for a specified period of time.
24 b. Working in a specified geographical area.
25 c. Engaging in work activities similar to those performed for the
26 employer.
27 (3) No-poach agreement. – An agreement between employers that restricts one
28 employer from soliciting, recruiting, hiring, or otherwise competing for
29 employees employed by another employer.
30 (b) Policy. – It is the public policy of this State that any contract by which anyone is
31 restrained from exercising a lawful profession, trade, or business of any kind is to that extent void
32 and unenforceable, except as provided in subsection (c) of this section.
33 (c) Prohibition. – No employer in this State shall do any of the following:
34 (1) Enter into a non-compete agreement with an employee.
*H269-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) Require an employee to enter into a non-compete agreement as a condition of
2 employment.
3 (3) Enforce or attempt to enforce a non-compete agreement.
4 (4) Threaten to enforce a non-compete agreement.
5 (5) In the case of a franchise operator, enter into an agreement that restricts an
6 employee from moving between locations.
7 (d) Enforcement. – Any person injured by a violation of this section may bring a civil
8 action to recover actual damages, reasonable attorneys' fees and costs, and any other relief the
9 court deems appropriate. The Attorney General may investigate violations and bring an action to
10 enforce this section.
11 (e) Choice of Law and Venue. – No employer may require an employee who primarily
12 resides or works in North Carolina to agree to a contract provision that would (i) require the
13 employee to adjudicate outside of North Carolina a claim arising in this State or (ii) deprive the
14 employee of the protection of North Carolina law for a claim arising in this State. Any such
15 provision is void and unenforceable."
16 SECTION 3.1.(b) Effective Date. – This section becomes effective July 1, 2025, and
17 applies to all non-compete agreements entered into on or after that date. This act does not apply
18 to non-compete agreements entered into prior to the effective date, except that any attempt to
19 enforce such an agreement after the effective date must comply with G.S. 95-275, as enacted by
20 this act.
21 SECTION 4.1.(a) LRC Study. – The Legislative Research Commission (LRC) shall
22 conduct a comprehensive review of all occupations and professions in North Carolina that require
23 a State-issued license. The purpose of this study is to identify any occupational licensing
24 requirements that are unnecessary or overly restrictive and to recommend changes to increase
25 workforce freedom while protecting public health and safety. For purposes of this section,
26 "occupational licensing board" has the same meaning as in G.S. 93B-1(2), and "licensed
27 profession" means any occupation or profession for which an individual is required by law to
28 obtain a license, certification, or registration from an occupational licensing board or other State
29 agency.
30 SECTION 4.1.(b) Scope. – The study conducted by the LRC under this section shall
31 examine and evaluate, at a minimum, the following criteria for each licensed profession. The
32 study shall be conducted with an emphasis on the following priority industries: construction
33 trades, cosmetology, health-related professions, personal care services, and other fields where
34 occupational licensing requirements may disproportionately impact small business creation and
35 workforce entry:
36 (1) Public safety rationale. – Whether the absence of a licensing requirement for
37 the profession would likely result in significant harm or danger to the public's
38 health, safety, or welfare. The review shall determine whether licensing is
39 justified by a demonstrable need to prevent tangible harm to consumers or the
40 public, with a focus on data-driven risk assessments.
41 (2) Necessity and alternatives. – Whether existing licensure requirements
42 advance a meaningful public interest and are no more restrictive than
43 necessary to protect that interest. The study shall compare North Carolina's
44 licensing requirements to national standards and determine whether less
45 restrictive alternatives, such as certification, registration, bonding, or general
46 consumer protection laws, could adequately ensure public safety and welfare.
47 (3) Impact on employment and economic opportunity. – Assess the extent to
48 which licensing requirements create barriers to entry into the profession. The
49 study shall use quantitative benchmarks, for example average licensing fees
50 and educational requirements compared to national medians, to determine if
51 the cost, education, experience, or examination requirements unreasonably
Page 2 House Bill 269-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 impede individuals, particularly those with moderate or low incomes, from
2 pursuing lawful work without providing a proportional benefit to public
3 protection.
4 (4) Effects on consumers and competition. – The impact of the licensing
5 regulation on consumer costs, service availability, and market competition.
6 Any licensing rules that result in a ten percent (10%) or greater increase in
7 consumer prices or a fifteen percent (15%) or greater reduction in market
8 competition, based on a three-year review period, shall be flagged for potential
9 modification or repeal.
10 (5) National comparison and best practices. – How North Carolina's licensing
11 requirements for the profession compare to those in other states and to national
12 standards or model laws. Any licensing requirement that exceeds the national
13 average in cost, educational hours, or regulatory burden without clear
14 justification shall be included in the study's findings for possible reform.
15 (6) Regulatory overlap or redundancy. – Whether the profession is subject to
16 duplicative regulations or could be regulated under an umbrella with related
17 occupations. The study shall identify any overlap between boards or licenses
18 and evaluate the feasibility of consolidating boards or creating universal
19 licensing recognition for workers moving from out of state.
20 (7) Outcomes and accountability. – The evaluation of both the costs and benefits
21 of the licensing requirement shall be supported by historical data, including
22 review of disciplinary records, consumer complaints, and enforcement
23 actions. The LRC shall recommend repeal or modification of any licenses that
24 have minimal documented public safety benefits but impose significant
25 barriers to employment.
26 SECTION 4.1.(c) Stakeholder Engagement. – The LRC shall engage stakeholders,
27 including the following:
28 (1) Occupational licensing boards representing the professions under review.
29 (2) Industry associations for the respective licensed professions.
30 (3) Consumer advocacy groups and workforce development organizations.
31 (4) Small business owners and entrepreneurs affected by licensing rules.
32 (5) Workers and trade associations representing licensed professionals.
33 The LRC shall conduct at least three public hearings, one in each geographic region
34 of the State (Western, Central, and Eastern North Carolina), to gather public input and
35 recommendations. The LRC shall open a public comment period of at least 90 days during which
36 individuals, businesses, and organizations may submit feedback. Additionally, the LRC shall
37 consider and incorporate reforms implemented in other states that have successfully reduced
38 licensing burdens while maintaining consumer protection standards.
39 SECTION 4.1.(d) Report and Legislative Action. – The LRC shall submit an interim
40 report on the results of the study authorized by this section, including any recommended
41 legislation, to the 2025 General Assembly when it reconvenes for the 2026 session. The LRC
42 shall submit a final report to the 2027 General Assembly, which shall do all of the following:
43 (1) Specifically identify any occupational licenses or licensing requirements
44 deemed unnecessary or overly restrictive, with supporting data.
45 (2) Include legislative proposals for modifying, consolidating, or eliminating
46 licensing requirements where justified.
47 (3) Recommend any administrative actions that could streamline licensing
48 processes without legislative changes.
49 (4) Include an implementation time line for any recommended reforms.
